## Notes on best practice

- **Mint a fresh DOI for the corpus and a separate DOI for the code.** Zenodo handles this naturally if you set up two GitHub repos (one for the platform code, one for the dataset releases). The two DOIs cross-reference each other via `related_identifiers`.
- **Pick Apache-2.0 (code) and CC-BY-4.0 (dataset)** - both are widely accepted in DH/linguistics and compatible with the per-source licences (PROIEL CC-BY-NC-SA, Modern Greek ODC-BY, etc.) when you ship the corpus as derived metadata + alignment graph rather than redistributing the raw source texts.
- **Add the ORCID once you have it.** ORCIDs are how every funder / repository / publisher cross-references your work; mint one at https://orcid.org/register if you haven't already.
- **Pin a CHANGELOG.md** in the repo. Zenodo automatically lists each release; a clear changelog makes the diff between versions obvious.
- **Add the Zenodo deposition to the relevant Zenodo communities** (DARIAH, CLARIN, Digital Humanities) for extra discoverability. The `.zenodo.json` above already lists them.
